al functions and their zeros, complex numbers, and rational functions asymptotes.\n\n**Quest Instructions:**\n1. Study the slides on quadratic and polynomial functions.\n2. Solve problems involving:\n   - Finding zeros of polynomials.\n   - Sketching polynomial graphs given zeros and end behavior.\n   - Operations on complex numbers.\n   - Identifying vertical and horizontal asymptotes of rational functions.\n3. Write a short explanation of the Fundamental Theorem of Algebra and how it relates to zeros of polynomials.\n4. Complete a mini-project: Create 3 example polynomial functions, find their zeros (real and complex), and sketch the graphs.\n\n**Grading Rubric:**\n- **Understanding (35%)**: Correct explanation of zeros and the Fundamental Theorem of Algebra.\n- **Problem-solving (40%)**: Accurate polynomial zeros and graph sketches.\n- **Complex numbers work (15%)**: Correct operations on complex numbers.\n- **Completeness & neatness (10%)**: All parts submitted, well-organized.\n\n---\n\n### Week 3: Unit 3 - Exponential and Logarithmic Functions  \n**Topics:** Exponential functions, logarithms, properties of logarithms, and solving exponential-logarithmic equations.\n\n**Quest Instructions:**\n1. Review all provided materials on exponentials and logarithms.\n2. Complete a worksheet of problems:\n   - Converting between exponential and logarithmic forms.\n   - Using log properties (product, quotient, power).\n   - Solving exponential and logarithmic equations.\n3. Plot 2 examples each of exponential growth and decay functions.\n4. Explain in your own words the real-world applications of exponential models.\n\n**Grading Rubric:**\n- **Concept mastery (40%)**: Correct use of logarithm properties and solving equations.\n- **Graphs (30%)**: Accurate and labeled graphs of exponential functions.\n- **Explanation (20%)**: Clear, concise application descriptions.\n- **Presentation & effort (10%)**: Worksheet fully completed and neat.\n\n---\n\n### Week 4: Unit 4 - Trigonometry Basics  \n**Topics:** Radians and degrees, unit circle, right triangle trigonometry, graphs of sine and cosine.\n\n**Quest Instructions:**\n1. Study the unit circle and definitions of sine, cosine, and tangent.\n2. Perform exercises:\n   - Convert angles between radians and degrees.\n   - Find sine, cosine, and tangent values for standard angles.\n   - Graph sine and cosine functions and identify amplitude, period, phase shift.\n3. Create flashcards for trigonometric values of key angles.\n4. Solve 10 real-world problems involving right triangle trig or unit circle applications.\n\n**Grading Rubric:**\n- **Accuracy (40%)**: Correct conversions and trig value computations.\n- **Graphs (30%)**: Properly drawn and labeled trig graphs.\n- **Application problems (20%)**: Correct solutions with clear work shown.\n- **Preparation tools (10%)**: Quality and completeness of flashcards.\n\n---\n\n### Week 5: Unit 5 - Trigonometric Identities and Equations  \n**Topics:** Using identities, verifying identities, solving trig equations, sum and difference formulas.\n\n**Quest Instructions:**\n1. Review all trig identity proofs and strategies.\n2. Verify 5 different trigonometric identities step-by-step.\n3. Solve a set of 10 trig equations using identities and algebraic methods.\n4. Demonstrate understanding of sum and difference formulas through examples.\n\n**Grading Rubric:**\n- **Verification skill (35%)**: Accuracy and clarity verifying identities.\n- **Equation solving (45%)**: Correct solutions with full explanations.\n- **Formula application (15%)**: Proper use of sum/difference formulas.\n- **Clarity and neatness (5%)**: Organized solutions, easy to follow.\n\n---\n\n### Week 6: Unit 6 - Law of Sines and Law of Cosines  \n**Topics:** Using laws to solve triangles, applications.\n\n**Quest Instructions:**\n1. Learn the Law of Sines and Law of Cosines formulas.\n2. Solve a variety of problems:\n   - Find missing sides/angles in oblique triangles.\n   - Real-world application problems (navigation, architecture).\n3. Create a visual diagram for problems showing the triangle and labeled sides/angles.\n4. Summarize when to use Law of Sines vs. Law of Cosines.\n\n**Grading Rubric:**\n- **Problem accuracy (50%)**: Correct application of laws.\n- **Diagram quality (20%)**: Clear, labeled visual aids.\n- **Written summary (20%)**: Understanding of laws' scope.\n- **Neatness and completeness (10%)**: All problems and summaries submitted on time.\n\n---\n\n### Week 7 to Week 10: Units on Vectors, Matrices, Parametric Equations, Polar Coordinates, and 3D Geometry  \n**(I can provide detailed quests for these weeks upon request.)**\n\n---\n\n### Additional Notes for You\n\n- Since you have \"None\" for learning style and interests, all tasks use multimodal approaches: reading, writing, problem-solving, and simple presentations.\n- You can adjust the presentation parts to digital formats or hand-written, whichever you find easier.\n- If you want, I can help tailor the quests later once you identify interests or preferred learning styles.\n\n---\n\nPlease let me know if you want quests designed for specific weeks or units next, or if you want me to include more support for specific types of learners.\n\nWould you like me to start with Week 1 detailed instructions and rubric?"